  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="background:var(--bg);">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Radiators Liverpool: Common Questions</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Straight answers before you book.</p>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-orange">COST</span>How much does it cost to fit a new radiator in Liverpool?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>A standard double panel radiator supply and fit costs from £200 in Liverpool. This includes the radiator, all fittings, TRV and a system balance on completion. Labour only for a like-for-like swap starts from £80. Column and designer radiators cost more due to the higher supply cost. We provide a fixed-price quote before any work begins.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-navy">SIZING</span>How do I know what size radiator I need?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>Radiator size is calculated using a heat loss calculation based on the room's dimensions, ceiling height, number and size of windows, external wall construction and desired temperature. Liverpool's older Victorian and Edwardian properties with solid walls and poor insulation typically need larger radiators than modern properties. We size every radiator correctly and never guess.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-green">TRV</span>What is a TRV and do I need one on every radiator?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>A thermostatic radiator valve (TRV) controls the heat output of an individual radiator. Under <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/boiler-plus" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Boiler Plus regulations</a>, TRVs are required on all new radiator installations. They allow you to set different temperatures in different rooms, reducing heating bills by 10 to 15%. The <a href="https://energysavingtrust.org.uk/advice/thermostats-and-heating-controls/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Energy Saving Trust</a> recommends them on every radiator. We fit them from £50 per valve.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-orange">MOVE</span>Can you move a radiator to a different wall?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>Yes. We drain down the circuit, extend or reroute the pipework to the new wall position and rebalance the system. Relocation costs from £150 per radiator depending on the distance of the move and the complexity of the new pipework run. In Liverpool's Victorian terraces with solid walls, pipework is usually surface-mounted or run under floorboards.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-navy">COLD SPOTS</span>Why does my radiator have cold spots?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>Cold spots at the top indicate trapped air which can be fixed by bleeding. Cold spots in the middle or bottom indicate sludge build-up which requires the radiator to be chemically cleaned or replaced, and a power flush of the whole system to prevent it recurring. If bleeding the radiator does not resolve the problem, call us to diagnose the root cause.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><span class="faq-tag tag-green">BALANCE</span>Why is it important to balance the system after fitting a radiator?</summary>
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>Adding a new radiator changes the flow resistance of the whole heating circuit. Without rebalancing, hot water takes the path of least resistance, meaning some radiators will overheat while others stay cold. We balance the system on every installation by adjusting lockshield valves to ensure an even flow rate and temperature throughout your Liverpool property.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

