        <div class="copy-block">
          <h2>Radiator Installation in Liverpool's Victorian Properties</h2>
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">What type of radiator suits a Liverpool Victorian terrace?</h3>
          <p>Liverpool's Victorian and Edwardian terraces are distinctive in having solid external walls, limited wall space between windows and door frames, and original period features worth preserving. Column radiators are the most sympathetic choice for period properties as they replicate the original cast-iron radiators and provide excellent heat output. Double panel convectors are a cost-effective alternative where period aesthetics are less important. We advise on the best option for each room at the free survey. The <a href="https://www.hse.gov.uk/gas/domestic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HSE domestic gas safety guidance</a> covers all pipework installation requirements we work to on every job.</p>
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">How many radiators does a typical Liverpool home need?</h3>
          <p>A standard 3-bed Liverpool terrace typically has 8 to 12 radiators including hallway, living room, kitchen, three bedrooms and bathroom. Larger semis and detached properties need more. Each room requires a correctly sized radiator based on a heat loss calculation, not a one-size-fits-all approach. Undersized radiators are the most common cause of cold rooms in Liverpool's older housing stock.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="copy-block">
          <h2>The Right Time to Replace Radiators in Liverpool</h2>
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">How long do radiators last?</h3>
          <p>A well-maintained steel panel radiator typically lasts 15 to 20 years. Cast-iron column radiators can last significantly longer. The key factor is system water quality: poor inhibitor levels and high levels of sludge and magnetite corrode radiator bodies from the inside, causing pinhole leaks that are often not visible until the radiator is removed. Annual boiler servicing and a system power flush every 5 to 7 years significantly extends radiator life. If your system is more than 15 years old and radiators are starting to fail, replacing the full system is often more cost-effective than individual replacements over time.</p>
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">Should I replace radiators when I get a new boiler?</h3>
          <p>Not necessarily. If the existing radiators are in good condition and the system is properly power flushed before the new boiler installation, the existing radiators can remain. However, if radiators are more than 15 years old, already showing signs of corrosion or are undersized for the rooms they heat, replacing them alongside the new boiler is significantly more cost-effective than returning at a later date when pipework would need to be disturbed again.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
